  "theory": {
    "explanation": "Adverbs in Present Perfect: ever, never, already, yet\n\nEVER = at any time\n  → in questions, after have/has: \"Have you ever been to Japan?\"\n\nNEVER = not ever\n  → in affirmative sentences (it negates by itself!)\n  → after have/has: \"I have never eaten sushi.\"\n\nALREADY = sooner than expected\n  → in affirmative sentences, after have/has: \"She has already left.\"\n\nYET = not yet / in questions\n  → at the end of a negative or interrogative sentence\n  → \"I haven't finished yet.\"  /  \"Has he arrived yet?\"",
    "examples": [
      {
        "sentence": "She never uses the dishwasher.",
        "explanation": "NEVER in an affirmative present simple sentence (3rd person singular → uses). It stands before the main verb."
      },
      {
        "sentence": "They've already booked the hotel.",
        "explanation": "ALREADY in an affirmative Present Perfect sentence. It comes after have/has, before the past participle."
      },
      {
        "sentence": "Have you spoken to your manager yet?",
        "explanation": "YET in a Present Perfect question. It comes at the end of the sentence."
      }
    ]
  }
